# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bangla-drink
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bangla-drink/aam-panna] Unripe mango is a rich source of pectin, which gradually diminishes after the formation of the stone.
[src:bangla-drink/aam-panna] Unripe mango is sour in taste because of the presence of oxalic, citric and malic acids.
[src:bangla-drink/aam-panna] Aam panna or Aam Jhora, which is prepared using raw mangoes, cumin, and an assortment of other spices, quenches thirst and prevents the excessive loss of sodium chloride and iron during summer due to excessive sweating.
[src:bangla-drink/aam-panna] The drink is mainly consumed in north India and Pakistan is considered beneficial in the treatment of gastrointestinal disorders.
[src:bangla-drink/aam-panna] It is also a good source of vitamin B1 and B2, niacin, and vitamin C.
[src:bangla-drink/aam-panna] In Indian and Pakistani culture, it is regarded as a tonic believed to increase resistance against tuberculosis, anemia, cholera and dysentery.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Commercial almond milk comes in sweetened, unsweetened, vanilla and chocolate flavors, and is usually fortified with micronutrients as a processed food.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Almond milk can also be made at home using a blender, almonds and water.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Global almond milk sales in 2018 were US$5.8 billion, growing at 14% per year, and forecast to be a $13 billion global market by 2025.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] The earliest recipes for almond milk date back to at least the 13th century Middle East, as it was listed in Muhammad bin Hasan al-Baghdadi’s book *Kitāb al-Ṭabīḫ* (كتاب الطبيخ; *The Book of Dishes*), written in 1226.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Almond milk was used as a substitute for animal milk in the Middle Ages in areas that followed Catholic fasting laws.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Some recipes for almond milk have used wine in the process.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Almond milk's popularity as a dairy substitute continued throughout history, going well into modern times.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] It is even mentioned under the secondary definition of "milk" in Samuel Johnson's *Dictionary* in 1755, alongside pistachio milk.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] In the United States, almond milk remained a niche health food item until the early 2000s, when its popularity began to increase.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] In 2011 alone, almond milk sales increased by 79%.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] In 2013, it surpassed soy milk as the most popular plant-based milk in the US.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] As of 2014 it comprised 60 percent of plant-milk sales and 4.1 percent of total milk sales in the US.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Manufacturers and distributors of animal milk have advocated that plant-based milk not be labelled as "milk".
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] They complain that consumers may be confused between the two, and that plant-based milks are not necessarily as nutritious in terms of vitamins and minerals.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] In the case of the United States, the FDA said in 2023 that plant-based milk could be labeled as milk, but that producers should note the nutritional differences from regular milk.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] European Union regulations require "milk" to be used for animals only, except coconut milk.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Within the Italian regions of Sicily, Apulia, Calabria, and Campania, almond milk is a protected traditional agricultural product.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Vitamin A fortification is only required for skimmed milk in the US.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Vitamin D fortification for milk is mandatory in the US.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] If unfortified, almond milk has less vitamin D than fortified cow milk; in North America, cow milk must be fortified with vitamin D, but vitamins are added to plant milks on a voluntary basis.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Vitamin E is released from the almonds and absorbed.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] The positive effects of the vitamin E include strengthening the cells.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Because of its low protein content (0.4 g per 100 ml), almond milk is not a suitable replacement for breast milk, cow milk, or hydrolyzed formulas for children under two years of age.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] The general production method involves soaking and grinding almonds in an excess of water.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] A milky white liquid is obtained after filtering the almond pulp (flesh).
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Almond milk can also be made by adding water to almond butter.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] In commercial production, almond milk is homogenised with high pressure and pasteurised for greater stability and shelf life.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Almond milk can be stored in the fridge in an air-tight container (preferably a glass container) for about 4–5 days.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] However, certain factors, such as the temperature of the refrigerator, sterilization of the blender or storing jar, and surface cleanliness, can decide how many days you can keep it fresh.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Storing homemade almond milk for more than a week may reduce its nutrition or even make it unhealthy.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] In July 2015, a class action lawsuit was filed in New York City against two American manufacturers, Blue Diamond Growers and White Wave Foods, for false advertising regarding the small quantity of almonds (only 2%) contained in the final product.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] In October 2015, a judge denied the plaintiff's request for an injunction.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Almond production in California is concentrated mainly in the Central Valley, where the mild climate, rich soil, and abundant sunshine and water supply make for ideal growing conditions.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Due to the persistent droughts in California in the early 21st century, it became more difficult to raise almonds in a sustainable manner.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Almond sustainability is challenged because of the high amount of water needed to grow almonds: a single glass of almond milk requires roughly 74 litres (16 imp gal; 20 US gal) of water to produce.
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Among plant-based milks, almond milk requires substantially more water during the growing and production stages than soy, rice or oat milk (graph).
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] Dairy milk requires more water to produce than almond milk (graph).
[src:bangla-drink/almond-milk] In 2014, California produced 42.3 billion pounds of cow's milk and only 2.14 billion pounds of almond milk.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Many tribal communities of Arunachal Pradesh use apo during their respective festivals, such as nyokum.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The tribal people offer the drink, every time they drink it, to the uiyu (spirits) by letting a few drops of it fall on the ground.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Other occasions when Apo is served include annually organized ancestor worship ceremonies, the festivals of Ali aye ligang, Nyokum, Dree, and others, and annual agricultural programs.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Apo is known in different names across different tribes in North-Eastern India, such as haaz (Ahom), apong (Mising), zou (zu mai) (Bodo) and Sujen (Deori).
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Apo is not distributed in shops, as apo forms part of a tradition and culture, the apo is shared through generations like a piece of cultural knowledge.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Apos are commonly brewed in households and often served along with rice and chutney as well, irrespective of gender or age differences.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The origins of the apo tradition in the North-Eastern regions are not recorded, However, the tradition may date back to Neolithic period.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Similarly, the word Apo is not a general term for a rice-based drink, as each tribe identifies the drink with different names.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] However, it is believed that the traditional rice beer was first developed by the 'Mising people in Assam.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Thus the etymology of the word refers to its Mising language origins.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Across the different tribes, the brewing method has certain differences, but the substrates used for fermentation are the same.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] This indicates a common ancestor to the brewing culture in North-Eastern India.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Traditionally, two kinds of Apo are being brewed in these regions known as Po:ro Apong and Nogin Apong.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The starter cakes called épob are made out of crushed rice and medicinal plants are used to make the health quotient.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] These starter cakes are one of the most important elements of the rice beers made in the North-Eastern region, including Apo.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] This also refers to the idea of sacredness associated with the Apo making across different tribes as it is not made on an everyday basis, but only for ceremonies, festivals, marriage, and group gatherings.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] In this regard, historically and culturally, the Apo remains as an element of identity in these regions.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Apo is known in different traditional names based on the respective tribes.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Apo is believed to be first developed by the Mising people in Assam.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The term Apo is derived from the traditional name "Apong" in the Mising language.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The Mising community is generally known for its passion for traditional cooking methods and food items.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The cooking method of the Apo is also believed to be shared by the ancestors of Mising community and later spread throughout the tribes in North East India.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Apo is commonly produced in households of northeastern states of Arunachal Pradesh and Assam in India.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Although distinctive methods for brewing exist across the North-Eastern region of India, the process of fermentation remains the same across these regions, indicating common origins of brewing.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] As a first step, the rice collected for making beverage is cooked and then mixed with ash from burnt paddy sticks, which makes the mixture black.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Once the rice is cooked, it is mixed with the fermenting ingredient E-Pob made out of rice and medicinal plants.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Time is taken for the formation of ration changes along with the climate and temperature.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] During summer, the fermentation took 5–6 days.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The fermented mixture is filtered and finally poured into bamboo shoots.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] During these processes, around 30 medicinal plants use to the beverage along with rice.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] This includes leaves, creepers, and grass.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The total period taken for the production of Apo beer is more than 3 months.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Although the alcohol content on the Apo is 18-25% it is more intoxicating in nature.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Recent studies indicate the Apo Beer can be economically benefiting the community as the beer provides the entrepreneurial potential to the community as the rice beer produced in Northeast regions, including Apo are high quality in nature.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The starter cake is one of the most indispensable elements of the Apo beer production process.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The Apo beer produced by the Mising community is identified to have various medicinal and therapeutic properties as a result often used during the preparation of starter cake known as épob.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The beer-making process in each tribe varies according to the environmental factors and other socio-cultural practices associated with the individual tribes.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] These factors are essential in determining the colour, flavour, and sweetness of the flower.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] One major process during the production of Apong is the use of starter cake, i.e. épob which has significant medicinal qualities.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] This quality is of starter cake is determined by the medicinal plants used during the production along with the sanitary conditions used while making the beer.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The making of épob in this regard include the process of collecting a variety of medicinal plant leaves.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The leaves collected are dried placing it on a bamboo mat known as époh after cleaning it.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Fresh leaves can also be used for making the starter cake for making the beer.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The leaves are later ground separately using a wooden tool hand mixer together to make an épob in the shape of oval-shaped balls from the dough made from the mixture.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The folk medicine beliefs of the starter cake derive from the use of local herbs.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Tribes believe that the combination of herbs makes Apo beer an effective agent against various minor diseases.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Most of the plants used for the preparation of the beer are indigenous.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The varieties of Apo beer in the northeast region of India include methods of infusion and decoction used by the local peoples.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Apo is an important element in the socio-cultural aspect of the Mising people.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] The Apo beer is served during religious festivals and ceremonies in Assam such as Marriages, death ceremonies, Ali A:yé Lígang, Porag, and other major community gatherings and celebration.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Apong is usually served along with pork and Purang apin in festivals like Ali A:yé Lígang.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] In local markets, Apo beer is a source of income and livelihood for many families, and contributes to community development.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] In Assam, it has been reportedly found to be sold by local brewers in small bottles.
[src:bangla-drink/apo-drink] Apo was featured in the Indian Amazon Prime Video web series *The Family Man* (season 3), where it is depicted as a traditional rice-based alcoholic beverage consumed in Northeast India.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] There are two primary styles of arrack that are very different from one another: *Batavia arrack* is often clear in color but has a flavor profile more similar to dark rum, with a distinctive "funk" or "hogo" imparted to it from fermented red rice.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Sri Lankan (Ceylon) arrack, by contrast, is a more refined and subtle spirit.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] It has hints of cognac and rum character and a wealth of delicate floral notes.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Both styles are also made "in house" by local citizenry and can be more akin to moonshine in their presentation.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The word derived from the Arabic word *arak* (عرق, *ʿaraq*), meaning 'distillate'.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] In the Eastern Mediterranean, the term *arak* is usually used for liquor distilled from grapes and flavored with anise.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The word "arrack" has been considered by some experts to be derived from *areca nut*, a palm seed originating in India from the areca tree and used as the basis for many varieties of arrack.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] In 1838, Samuel Morewood's work on the histories of liquors was published.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] He notes several examples of the word and its derivatives among other ethnic groups: the Tungusians, Calmucks, and Kirghizes use the terms "arrack" or "rak", and the Ossetians "applied the word 'Arak' to denote all distilled liquors".
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Strabo reports Indians made a beverage from rice known as arak.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Arrack predates all "New World" spirits, as it is a parent to cachaça (which was, in turn, the parent of rum, rhum agricole, and ron).
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Genoese merchants made the spirit as a byproduct of their sugar cane production in the Canary Islands.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] In addition to making sugar, they produced arrack instead of importing it for their growing list of customers.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Other early arrack was distilled from molasses and water, using dried cakes of red rice and botanicals that contained yeast and other fungi to trigger the fermentation process (this technique can be traced back thousands of years to China and even predates the birth of distillation).
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] It is also claimed to have been distilled in India in 800 BCE, but while palm wine and fermented sugarcane drinks were being made around this time, not all believe that formal distillation was taking place.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Outside Asia, the spirit was a common ingredient in the proliferation of Indian alcoholic punch, and was particularly popular in Holland and Sweden.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] It was the first distilled spirit consumed in colonial America, in the colonies of New Sweden and New Netherland, but is now mostly confused with the more common and similar spelled anise-flavored spirit arak.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Regardless of the exact origin, arrack has come to symbolize a multitude of largely unrelated, distilled alcohols produced throughout Asia and the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] This is largely due to the proliferation of distillation knowledge throughout the Middle East during the 14th century.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Each country named its own alcohol by using various Latin alphabet forms of the same word that was synonymous with distillation at the time (*arak, araka, araki, ariki, arrack, arack, raki, raque, racque, rac, rak*).
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] 1864 English and Australian Cookery Book described arrack as "a spirituous liquor from the East Indies.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] This term, or its corruption, rack, is applied to any spirituous liquor in the East.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The true arrack is said to be distilled from *toddy*, the fermented juice of the coconut flower.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Arrack was banned in the states of Kerala in 1996, and Karnataka on 1 July 2007.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Within Indonesia itself, the term *arak* is still widely used to describe arrack.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Arak (or rice wine) was a popular alcoholic beverage during the colonial era.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] It is considered the "rum" of Indonesia because, like rum, it is distilled from sugarcane.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] To start the fermentation, local fermented red rice is combined with local yeast to give a unique flavor and smell of the distillate.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] It is distilled to approximately 70% ABV.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Like rum, Batavia-arrack is often a blend of different original parcels.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] One of the longest established arrack companies in Indonesia is the Batavia Arak Company (Dutch *Batavia-Arak Maatschappij*), which was already in business by 1872, became a limited liability company in 1901, and was still operating in the early 1950s.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The Batavia Arak Company also exported arrack to the Netherlands and had an office in Amsterdam.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Some of the arrack brands produced by Batavia Arak Company were KWT (produced in the Bandengan [Kampung Baru] area of old Jakarta) and OGL.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Still commonly available in Northern Europe and Southern Asia, Batavia-arrack can be difficult to find in the United States.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] *Batavia-Arrack van Oosten* is a more recently available brand.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Batavia-arrack is said to enhance flavor when used as a component in other products, such as pastries (like the Finnish Runeberg torte or the Dresdner Stollen), or in the confectionery and flavor industries.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] It is used in herbal and bitter liqueurs, and as a component in alcoholic punches (such as punsch, regent punch, royal punch, and black tea-port milk punch).
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Its use in punch was noted by early American bartender Jerry Thomas: "Most of the arrack imported into this country is distilled from rice, and comes from Batavia.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] It is but little used in America, except to flavor punch; the taste of it is very agreeable in this mixture.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] It is much used in some parts of India, where it is distilled from toddy, the juice of the coconut tree".
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] In Indonesia, arrack is often created as a form of moonshine.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Indonesian arrack containing methanol has caused both local and tourist deaths from methanol toxicity.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Arrack plays a socially and culturally important role in Balinese society, where it is often diluted with water, shared with friends, or drunk in small quantities during religious ceremonies.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] However, with the growth of tourism, the need for cheap alcohol, and increases in alcohol import taxes and regulations, arrack became the spirit of choice for many mixed drinks in bars.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] With the growth in arrack production and popularity, more deaths from methanol poisoning were reported.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Arrack is usually sold on the black market, without regulation, where methanol is sometimes added for economic reasons, or out of the assumption that it will be more potent.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] A Filipino term for distilled and undistilled alcoholic drinks in general is *alak*, derived from the Arabic word *ʿaraq*.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The term *arak*, though, is specifically used in Ilocano.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] It can be derived from palm sap (notably coconut, nipa palm, or kaong palm), sugarcane, or rice.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Traditionally distilled native alcohols include lambanóg and laksoy, which are made from the sap of palm flowers.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The sap is harvested into bamboo receptacles similar to rubber tapping, then cooked or fermented to produce a mildly-alcoholic coconut toddy called *tubâ*.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The *tubâ*, which by itself is also a popular beverage, is further distilled to produce lambanóg (or laksoy, if made from nipa palm sap).
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The Italian explorer Antonio Pigafetta stated that the arrack that he drank in Palawan and nearby islands in 1521 was made from distilled rice wine.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] However, he was likely referring to *pangasi*, an undistilled rice wine.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Sri Lanka is the largest producer of coconut arrack and, until 1992, the government played a significant role in its production.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Other than water, the entire manufacturing process revolves around the fermentation and distillation of a single ingredient, the sap of unopened flowers from a coconut palm (*Cocos nucifera*).
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Each morning at dawn, men known as toddy tappers move among the tops of coconut trees using connecting ropes not unlike tightropes.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] A single tree may contribute up to two litres per day.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Due to its concentrated sugar and yeast content, the captured liquid naturally and immediately ferments into a mildly alcoholic drink called "toddy", *tuak*, or occasionally "palm wine".
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Within a few hours after collection, the toddy is poured into large wooden vats, called "washbacks", made from the wood of teak or Berrya cordifolia.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The natural fermentation process is allowed to continue in the washbacks until the alcohol content reaches 5–7% and deemed ready for distillation.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Distillation is generally a two-step process involving either pot stills, continuous stills, or a combination of both.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The first step results in "low wine", a liquid with an alcohol content between 20 and 40%.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The second step results in the final distillate with an alcohol content of 60 to 90%.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] It is generally diluted to between 33% and 50% alcohol by volume (ABV) or 66 to 100 proof.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The entire distillation process is completed within 24 hours.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Various blends of coconut arrack diverge in processing, yet the extracted spirit may also be sold raw, repeatedly distilled or filtered, or transferred back into halmilla vats for maturing up to 15 years, depending on flavour, colour and fragrance requirements.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Premium blends of arrack add no other ingredients, while the inexpensive and common blends are mixed with neutral spirits before bottling.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Most people describe the taste as resembling "... a blend between whiskey and rum", similar, but distinctively different at the same time.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Coconut arrack is traditionally consumed by itself or with ginger beer, a popular soda in Sri Lanka.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] It also may be mixed in cocktails as a substitute for the required portions of either rum or whiskey.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Arrack is often combined with popular mixers such as cola, soda water, and lime juice.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Ceylon Arrack, a brand of Sri Lankan coconut arrack, was recently launched in the UK in 2010.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] It is also available in France and Germany.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] White Lion VSOA entered the American market soon after.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Historically arrack has been a common beverage on the island of Saint Helena, distilled from potatoes.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] This is likely due to influences of the East India Company, which controlled Saint Helena and used it as a halfway point between India and England.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] In Sweden and Finland, Batavia-arrack has historically been mixed with other ingredients in order to make Swedish punsch (now available in prepackaged bottles).
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The alcohol content is normally not over 25%, although it has a high sugar content of nearly 30%.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The original recipe was a mixture of arrack with water, sugar, lemon, and tea or spices (chiefly nutmeg).
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] Today punsch is drunk warm (in Sweden) or cold (in Finland) as an accompaniment to yellow split pea soup (in Sweden) or green split pea soup (in Finland), or chilled as an after dinner drink accompanied with coffee (especially during dinner parties at student nations).
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] It is used as a flavouring in several types of pastries and sweets as well.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] The name arrack is still retained for some pastries, for example *arraksboll*, whereas punsch is used for things like *punschrulle*.
[src:bangla-drink/arrack] In Finland, arrack (or rum) usually serves as one of the ingredients in the making one of the Finnish traditional pastries, Runeberg tortes.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] The state of Assam is the world's largest tea-growing region by production, lying on either side of the Brahmaputra River, and bordering Bhutan, Bangladesh, Myanmar and very close to China.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] This part of India experiences high rainfall; during the monsoon period, as much as 250 to 300 mm (10 to 12 in) of rain falls per day.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] The daytime temperature rises to about 36 °C (96.8 °F), creating greenhouse-like conditions of extreme humidity and heat.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] This tropical climate contributes to Assam tea's unique malty taste, a feature for which this tea is well known.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Though *Assam* generally denotes the distinctive black teas from Assam, the region produces smaller quantities of green and white teas as well, with their own distinctive characteristics.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Historically, Assam has been the second commercial tea production region after southern China, the only two regions in the world with native tea plants.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] The introduction of the Assam tea bush to Europe is related to Robert Bruce, a Scottish adventurer, who apparently encountered it in the year 1823.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Bruce reportedly found the plant growing "wild" in Assam while trading in the region.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Maniram Dewan directed him to the local Singpho chief Bessa Gam.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Bruce noticed local people (the Singhpos) brewing tea from the leaves of the bush and arranged with the local chiefs to provide him with samples of the leaves and seeds, which he planned to have scientifically examined.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Robert Bruce died shortly thereafter, without having seen the plant properly classified.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] It was not until the early 1830s that Robert's brother, Charles, arranged for a few leaves from the Assam tea bush to be sent to the botanical gardens in Calcutta for proper examination.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] There, the plant was finally identified as a variety of tea, or *Camellia sinensis* var *assamica*, but different from the Chinese version (*Camellia sinensis* var.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] The indigenous Assam tea plant was first mentioned by a historian called Samuel Baidon who published *Tea in Assam* in 1877.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] While on a trade expedition through the Assam area with Singpho in 1823, Robert Bruce was introduced to a plant with which the Singpho and Khamti people made beverages and food.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Through his brother, Charles Alexander Bruce who was in Sadiya, samples were sent to botanist Nathaniel Wallich who mistook it for *camellia kissi*.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Charles Bruce guided a team, including Nathaniel Wallich, William Griffith and John McClelland, dispatched from the Tea Committee in 1836, to review the plant in its natural growing conditions around Sadiya.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] It was cultivated in the company's experimental garden with the first batch shipped to London in 1838 and auctioned in January 1839.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Though it sold well the batch was noted as lacking fragrance compared to the tea from China which had been selectively cultivated for hundreds of years and having a dullness thought to be a consequence of inexperienced processing.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] That same year, two companies were incorporated to pursue the tea's development in Assam: the Assam Tea Association in London and the Bengal Tea Association in Kolkata, though they quickly amalgamated to form the Assam Company.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Despite early proponents such as Maniram Dewan, British-led land reforms such as the *Waste Lands Act* to clear and privatize plots of land for agricultural purposes, the Assam Company struggled and was forced to reorganize in 1847.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Similarly, despite having access to a large source of inexpensive labour, including tea-makers smuggled out of China, indentured Indians, and refugees from famine-stricken areas, Assam at the time was a sparsely populated, hot and humid undeveloped area and many died of disease.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Despite the poor results, investment came from Britain to establish additional tea gardens, such as the Jorehaut Tea Company around Jorhat, in 1860s though by 1870 56 of the 60 companies operating tea gardens in Assam went bankrupt.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Industrial mechanization in the 1870s finally resulted in profitable companies as more plucked leaves were able to be dried without rotting in the humid environment.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Heated withering tables and steam-powered rolling machines precipitated a need for grading so the British adapted the existing systems of tea leaf grading to sort their products.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] The Indian Tea Districts Association was established in London in 1879 and in Kolkata in 1881 (as the Indian Tea Association) to organize and advance these tea interests.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] By 1888 tea imported from India finally exceeded that from China.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Most of the currently operating tea estates in Assam are members of the Assam Branch of the Indian Tea Association (ABITA), which is the oldest and most prominent body of tea producers of India.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] There are between two and seven steps involved in the processing of fresh tea leaves, the addition or exclusion of any of these stages resulting in a different type of tea.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Each of these procedures is carried out in a climate-controlled facility to avoid spoilage due to excess moisture and fluctuating temperatures.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Tea gardens in Assam do not follow the Indian Standard Time (IST), which is the time observed throughout India and Sri Lanka.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] The local time in Assam's tea gardens, known as "Tea Garden Time" or *Sah Bagan Time* (also used by Myanmar as MMT), is an hour ahead of the IST.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] The system was introduced during British rule keeping in mind the early sunrise in this part of the country.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] By and large, the system has subsequently been successful in increasing the productivity of tea garden workers as they save on daylight by finishing the work during daytime, and vice versa.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Working time for tea laborers in the gardens is generally between 9 a.m.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] (IST 4 p.m.) It may vary slightly from garden to garden.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Noted filmmaker Jahnu Barua has been campaigning for a separate time zone for the northeast region.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] The tea plant is grown in the lowlands of Assam, unlike Darjeelings and Nilgiris, which are grown in the highlands.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] It is cultivated in the valley of the Brahmaputra River, an area of clay soil rich in the nutrients of the floodplain.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] The climate varies between a cool, arid winter and a hot, humid rainy season—conditions ideal for growing tea.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Because of its long growing season and generous rainfall, Assam is one of the most prolific tea-producing regions in the world.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Each year, the tea estates of Assam collectively yield approximately 680.5 million kg (1,500 million pounds weight) of tea.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] Assam tea is generally harvested twice, in a "first flush" and a "second flush".
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] The first flush is picked during late March.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] The second flush, harvested later, is the more prized "tippy tea", named thus for the gold tips that appear on the leaves.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] This second flush, tippy tea, is sweeter and more full-bodied and is generally considered superior to the first flush tea.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] The leaves of the Assam tea bush are dark green and glossy and fairly wide compared to those of the Chinese tea plant.
[src:bangla-drink/assam-tea] The bush produces delicate white blossoms.
[src:bangla-drink/bangla-drink] Bangla is made from grains such as sorghum, bajra and wheat.
[src:bangla-drink/bangla-drink] According to the government data of 2015, 48% of the West Bengal state's market share is Indian-made foreign liquor (IMFL), 39% is the Bangla drink.
[src:bangla-drink/bangla-drink] 11% of the market share is beer and the remaining 2% are occupied by wine and other spirits.
[src:bangla-drink/bangla-drink] Bangla is generally consumed by those who cannot afford other more expensive alcohol.
[src:bangla-drink/bangla-drink] The market, however, has been increasing for domestic liquor; this is due to a combination of a change in government policy that allows Bengali liquor to be sold in more outlets, improved production, better packaging, and new marketing strategies.
[src:bangla-drink/bangla-drink] A major proportion of excise revenue in the state of West Bengal comes from cheap Bengali liquor.
[src:bangla-drink/bangla-drink] In the 2014-15 fiscal year, the figure reached 3,600 crore.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] In recent years, the traditional Indian goli soda or banta soda industry has seen a revival, driven by urban nostalgia and growing consumer interest in heritage beverages.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Modern brands are reintroducing these marble-sealed drinks with a variety of flavours, contemporary packaging, and wider retail and online distribution.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Among the companies contributing to this trend is Chimp Soda, which produces flavoured goli sodas and distributes them through retail channels and online at chimpsoda.com.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] The industry reflects a broader effort to modernize a classic Indian soft drink while retaining its distinctive, refreshing taste.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Due to the continued popularity, the bottle and drink have become part of Indian popular culture.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] The *Banta Soda* is popular in Delhi, Punjab and Uttar Pradesh; and its variation the *Panneer Soda*, which is mixed with rose water, is popular in Tamil Nadu and Andhra Pradesh.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] In Delhi it is known as "Delhi's local drink", where it remains popular, especially in Old Delhi and the Delhi University college campuses.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Due to its popularity, it is also available in "fancy" bars, and commercially mass-manufactured versions in several flavours are also available.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] The drink gets its name from the marble in the Codd-neck bottle.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] The marble in Hindi and Punjabi is known as the banta, goli, goti, kancha, etc., hence the names, *Banta Soda* and *Goti Soda* – as the drink is known in North India, and the *Goli Soda* – as the drink is known in South India.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] In Delhi, it is also called the *kanchay waali drink* or *nimbu soda*.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] *Fotash Jawl* is the Bengali name for this drink.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] The Codd-neck bottle, named after its inventor Hiram Codd who patented it in 1872, was specially designed for lemonade and fizzy beverages.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] The bottles, which soon became popular throughout the British Empire, are nowadays still in production for two countries exclusively: in India for banta and in Japan for *ramune*.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Since children often smashed the bottles to get to the marble inside, old Codd-neck bottles are cherished collector's items.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Until the 1900s, when the manufacturing of these bottles started in India, the bottles were imported from Britain.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Prior to India's independence in 1947, the bottles were banned in several cities during the Indian independence movement as the Indian freedom fighters added chuna (calcium hydroxide) to the soda bottles for making improvised mini cannons.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] In 1950s, banta soda was sold on horse-drawn carts which also carried the soda-making equipment.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Ingredients such as salt and water are mixed with the flavours using either the fresh fruit juice or commercial flavours, which is then poured into a Codd-neck bottle using a funnel until the bottle is full.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] In the 21st century, traditional Indian marble-sealed beverages known as goli soda or banta soda have experienced a revival driven by nostalgia and renewed interest in regional drinks.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Once commonly sold by street vendors across India, the beverage has re-emerged through small beverage manufacturers and startup brands that aim to modernize the product while retaining its distinctive marble-stoppered bottle.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] These companies have introduced new fruit flavours, improved bottling processes, and expanded distribution through supermarkets and online retail platforms.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Several contemporary brands have participated in this revival by reintroducing goli soda to urban markets and younger consumers.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Among them is Chimp Goli Soda, which produces flavoured marble-bottle beverages and distributes them through retail channels and its website, chimpsoda.com or chimpgolisoda.com.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Such brands reflect a broader trend in India’s beverage sector toward reviving traditional drinks while adapting them for modern packaging, branding, and e-commerce distribution and international export markets.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] The brand emphasizes retaining the traditional nostalgic taste of goli soda while appealing to global audiences seeking refreshing, heritage-inspired beverages.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Chimp Soda’s export strategy targets countries with significant Indian diaspora as well as consumers interested in unique cultural beverages, reflecting a broader trend of traditional Indian drinks reaching international markets.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Like *ramune*, a drink available in Japan, banta soda in India is also available in a Codd-neck bottle, a heavy glass bottle whose mouth is sealed by a round marble (instead of a cap) thanks to the pressure of the carbonated contents.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] The distinctive bottle has led to the drink also being called *goli soda* in South India.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Prior to India's independence the Codd-neck bottles were imported from England.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] However, post-independence local manufacturers came up, including many factories in Ahmedabad, all of which have now stopped making Codd-neck bottles.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Presently, Khandelwal Glass Works, who has been making these bottles since 1981 at Sasni in Uttar Pradesh, is the sole manufacturer of Codd-neck bottles in India after their competitor Mahalakshmi Glass Works in Hyderabad closed down a few years ago.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Before the re-entry of popular soft drinks, such as Pepsi and Coca-Cola in 1993, the sale of Banta reached its peak in the early 1990s, selling 100,000 bags per annum, with each bag containing 75 bottles.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] By 2010, however, the sales had dropped by nearly half.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] During the bottling process, a chemical flavouring agent known as Lemon No.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] 1 by International Flavors & Fragrances (IFF) is added.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] The agent is also used in ice cream and by the pharmaceutical industry.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] The banta soda bottles are largely bottled by unorganized manufacturers, who sell bottles for as little as ₹2 (2.1¢ US).
[src:bangla-drink/banta] In 2017, Delhi had over 100 single-room bottling units.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] In 1970s, Chennai had 150 goli soda bottling units in the unorganised sector which had dropped to 50 by 2018.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Chennai-based Kozzmo Beverages, which started its operations in 2018, has started making commercial pre-packaged hygienic goli soda using a manufacturing unit certified by the Food Safety and Standards Authority of India (FSSAI).
[src:bangla-drink/banta] It sells 6 flavours – paneer soda, nimbu masala, lemon, orange, grape, and pineapple.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Spark Premium Codd Soda introduced the first premium branded *goli soda* in Telangana.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] Mohammed Abdul Khader, who started manufacturing Spark Goli Soda in 2019 says it took him two years to get into selling business-to-business.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] On the disappearance of *goli soda*, he says, "One factor was the traditional filling system.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] It was cumbersome and needed a lot of manpower.
[src:bangla-drink/banta] The expensive production method contributed to its disappearance.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Beer-like sura has been produced in India since the Vedic era (c.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] 1500–1200 BCE, Rig Veda), rice beer has been produced by the native tribes since ancient times, European beer imports to India from England started in 1716, introduced by the British Raj].
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Lion beer, produced continuously since the 1820s, is Asia's first beer brand, and the first Indian brewed European style beer.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] The Vedas mention a beer-like drink called *sura*.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Megasthenes has recorded usage of rice beer in India.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Kautilya has also mentioned two intoxicating beverages made from rice called *Medaka* and *Prasanna*.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Rice beer or *handia* has been traditionally prepared by various indigenous tribes of India, in which *Ruellia suffruticosa* is sometimes added for flavor.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Rice beer also has ceremonial use among the Asur people.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Millet beer is also prepared by some tribes.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Haldane, local beer helped in keeping diseases like beri beri checked in these tribes.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Recently, government and social workers have been trying to curb alcohol usage among these tribes.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Elephant herds have been known to attack villages to drink this rice beer for which they have acquired a taste.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] European-style beer was introduced in India by the British.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] By 1716, pale ale and Burton ale were being imported to India from England.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] To protect the beer from spoiling during the long journey, it had to have high alcohol content and hops were added to it.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] This led to the invention of India pale ale in about 1787 by Bow Brewery.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Edward Dyer, travelled to back India and set up India's first brewery, the Kasauli Brewery.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] It produced the beer brand Lion, which is still available.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] The beer production at Kasauli brewery was moved to Solan Brewery at Solan in a swap when Kasauli Brewery started producing India's first single malt whisky, the Solan No.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In 1855, it was incorporated as Dyer Breweries.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Later, more breweries were built across India, Burma and Sri Lanka, and added to it.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Meakin bought the Solan brewery and added some more.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] It came to be known as Dyer-Meakin & Company.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] By the year 1882, there were 12 breweries in India in all, including one in Rangoon.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In the year 1892, 4,831,127 gallons of beer were produced in India.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Out of this 2,748,365 gallons were purchased by commissariat and rest was left for consumption by the civilian population.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] But, British soldiers reportedly did not like local beer and preferred imported beer which they were able to acquire cheaply.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In 1937, Burma was separated from India and the company lost its Burmese assets.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] The company was restructured and renamed as Dyer Meakin Breweries.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] It was listed on the London Stock Exchange.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] N Mohan acquired all the assets of Dyer Meakin Breweries and added a few more units.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In 1967, the company was renamed to Mohan Meakin Breweries.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Established in 1969, Lilasons Breweries in Madhya Pradesh is known for their strong beer brand Khajuraho.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] It is considered the first super-strong beer brand in India.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In recent years, foreign companies have been entering India and acquiring local businesses.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In 1999, United Breweries floated a subsidiary called Millennium AlcoBev.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] It was a joint venture between United Breweries, UK-based Scottish & Newcastle and Ravi Jain.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In 2000, SABMiller India entered Indian market by acquiring Narang Breweries.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In June 2001, it acquired the Mysore Breweries.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In 2003, SABMiller India acquired 50% stake in local Shaw Wallace's beer business.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In November 2002, SABMiller India acquired Rochees Breweries.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In May 2005, SABMiller India acquired Shaw Wallace's beer assets for ₹600 crore.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Also in 2005, Carlsberg entered India with its local venture, South Asian Breweries.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Also in 2005, Singapore-based Asia Pacific Breweries acquired a 76% shared the local Aurangabad Breweries.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In late 2005, UK-based Cobra Beer entered the Indian market by beginning negotiations with in December.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In 2006, SABMiller India acquired Foster's Indian assets.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In February 2006, Anheuser-Busch Inbev, the makers of Budweiser, entered a partnership with Hyderabad-based Crown Beers.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Also in 2006, Ravi Jain divested his holdings in Millennium AlcoBev.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In 2010, United Breweries consolidate its assets, merging Millennium AlcoBev and other units back into itself.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In 2011, United Breweries announced that they would produce the Heineken brand beer in India.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In 2012 after India allowed foreign-direct investment from Pakistan, Murree Beer representatives stated that they were seeking to export their brand to India.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] The Rawalpindi-based Murree Beer, which was established in 1861, has been trying to enter the Indian market since 2003.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] "Oktoberfest Goa", a beer, food and electronic music festival, has been held every year since 2011 in Goa.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] The Competition Commission of India found United Breweries Limited (UBL), Anheuser Busch InBev India Ltd.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] (AB InBev) and Carlsberg India Private Limited (CIPL) guilty of price fixing and imposed fines in September 2021.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] UBL and CIPL were fined ₹750 crore (US$79 million) and ₹120 crore (US$13 million) respectively, while AB InBev was given a 100% benefit of reduction in penalty.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] The largest selling India beer brand is Kingfisher.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Other major Indian brands are Hunter, Kalyani, Haywards, Knock Out and Zingaro.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] The largest brewery in India by market share is the Bangalore based United Breweries.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Other major breweries in India are Carlsberg, SABMiller India, B9 Beverages (Bira 91) Som Distilleries and Breweries Ltd and Anheuser-Busch Inbev.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In 2013, United Breweries had a market share of 55% and SABMiller India had a share of 23%.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] SABMiller India owns the Haywards brand, KALS breweries owns Foster's Indian units.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Although imported beer brands like, Corona, Singha, Tsingtao, Victoria Bitter, Geist and Christoffel, are available in India, they are costly due to high import duties reaching up to 100%.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Carlsberg's Tuborg Booster Strong brand (8% ABV) and Anheuser-Busch Inbev's Budweiser Magnum (6.5% ABV) are sold only in India.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] United Breweries' Kingfisher Strong (8% ABV) is India's best selling brand.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Modern craft beer came relatively late to India.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] The first Indian brewpubs opened in Pune (Doolally) and Gurgaon Ahirwal (Howzat) in 2009.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Also around the same time, India's first bottled craft beers were launched by the Martin Judd's brewery in Maharashtra, and Australian owned "Little Devils" in Ghaziabad.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] While the bottling ventures proved short-lived, and closed down within a years time, brewpubs have since become a successful format and common sight, especially in India's large cities.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In 2019, India counts more than 200 brewpubs, of which about 60 each are located in Bangalore and Gurgaon, respectively.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Bottled Indian craft beer became available again after a long break in 2016, when the White Rhino brewery opened in Gwalior, and soon after started selling their beers in Haryana and Delhi.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Since then, new packaging craft breweries have opened in Bangalore and Goa.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Due to restrictive Indian liquor manufacturing laws, some entrepreneurs have chosen to manufacture their beer outside of India.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Among them was Bira91, an Indian witbier brand, which became extremely popular across the country, and has since shifted its production back to India.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] In 2014-15 financial year, the beer market in India grew by 6% to 22.3 million hectolitres (or to 286 million cases).
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] On the one hand, this rate is twice faster as compared to the 2013-14-year; on the other hand, it is half than the average rate over the preceding decade.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] The per capita consumption of beer is 1.6 litres.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Due to the increase in disposable income and discerning consumers, the potential is high.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] The industry has been growing over the last few years and this growth is attributed to the growing middle class.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] The increased consumption has raised the price of barley in India.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Indians prefer stronger alcoholic drinks, like whiskey, over beer, because it is cheaper and has a higher alcohol content.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Strong beer with alcohol content in the 5-8% range accounted for 83% of the total beer sales in 2012.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Beer accounts for only 5% of the total alcohol consumed.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] The low consumption is attributed to high cost, availability and stringent regulations.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Karnataka and Kerala are the only two state in India which has a lower tax rate for beer compared to other alcoholic beverages.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Maharashtra has the highest tax on alcohol, at 43%.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] The latest entrant into the Indian market is the Bira 91 brand with its headquarters in Delhi, making a steady rise in the beer market.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Domestic-market beer is packaged in 650-ml bottles and come in cases of 6.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] Export-market beer come in 330-ml Standard European or 625-ml (22 imp. oz.) bottles.
[src:bangla-drink/beer-in-india] They come in mild (4% to 5% ABV) and strong (6% to 8% ABV) lagers.
